<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
	ws-review-multivariable-functions.ptx
	Section 0 (Multivariable Calculus Review), worksheet R1:
	Graphs and Level Sets — graphs as surfaces, level curves, level
	surfaces, and contour maps.

	Authored to the SHARED worksheet conventions
	(checklists/worksheet-conventions.md), NOT the legacy commentary
	pattern:
	  * reading-check blanks  -> paired <p component="stu"> (with <fillin>)
	    and <p component="key"> (answers as \underline{\textbf{...}});
	  * worked/practice problems -> paired <exercise component="stu"
	    workspace="Xin"> (statement + blank axes to sketch on) and
	    <exercise component="key"> (statement + <solution> with the answer
	    figure);
	  * a quick True/False -> one <exercise> + <solution component="key">.
	Figures are native TikZ/pgfplots <latex-image> (the notes
	<latex-image-preamble> in source/notes/bookends/docinfo.ptx loads tikz +
	pgfplots). Book concepts are tracked but example equations are NOT reused.
-->
<worksheet xml:id="ws-review-multivariable-functions">
	<title>Review: Graphs and Level Sets</title>

	<objectives>
		<ul>
			<li>Interpret the graph of a function of two variables as a surface in space.</li>
			<li>Sketch and interpret the <term>level curves</term> of a function of two variables.</li>
			<li>Describe the <term>level surfaces</term> of a function of three variables.</li>
			<li>Read a contour map to estimate function values and where a function changes fastest.</li>
		</ul>
	</objectives>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 1: Graphs of functions of two variables
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><alert>I. The graph of a function of two variables.</alert></p>

		<p>
			A scalar function <m>f(x,y)</m> takes a point <m>(x,y)</m> in its
			domain <m>D \subseteq \R^2</m> and returns a single real number.
			Its <term>graph</term> is the set of points
			<m>\big(x,y,f(x,y)\big)</m> in <m>\R^3</m>; as <m>(x,y)</m> ranges
			over <m>D</m> these points trace out a <term>surface</term> sitting
			above (and below) the <m>xy</m>-plane.
		</p>

		<!-- reading-check pair 1 -->
		<p component="stu">
			The graph of <m>y=g(x)</m> from Calculus 1 is a <fillin characters="6"/>
			<nbsp/>in the plane; the graph of <m>z=f(x,y)</m> is a
			<fillin characters="8"/> <nbsp/>in space. To plot the single point
			above <m>(x,y)=(a,b)</m> we move to height <m>z=</m>
			<fillin characters="8"/>.
		</p>
		<p component="key">
			The graph of <m>y=g(x)</m> is a <m>\underline{\textbf{curve}}</m>
			in the plane; the graph of <m>z=f(x,y)</m> is a
			<m>\underline{\textbf{surface}}</m> in space. The point above
			<m>(a,b)</m> sits at height <m>z=\underline{\textbf{f(a,b)}}</m>.
		</p>

		<p>
			Surfaces are hard to draw freehand, so we usually understand
			<m>z=f(x,y)</m> through two-dimensional slices instead. Slicing by
			the horizontal planes <m>z=c</m> and projecting each intersection
			straight down onto the <m>xy</m>-plane gives <em>level curves</em>
			(this worksheet); slicing by the vertical planes <m>x=a</m> or
			<m>y=b</m> gives <em>traces</em>.
		</p>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 2: Level curves
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><alert>II. Level curves.</alert></p>

		<p>
			The <term>level curve</term> of <m>f</m> at value <m>c</m> is the
			set of domain points where <m>f</m> equals <m>c</m>:
			<md>
				\{(x,y) \in D : f(x,y) = c\}.
			</md>
			It is a curve drawn in the <m>xy</m>-plane, one for each chosen
			<m>c</m>. A collection of them is a <term>contour map</term>, the
			same idea as the contour lines on a topographic map.
		</p>

		<!-- reading-check pair 2 -->
		<p component="stu">
			A level curve lives in the <fillin characters="10"/>
			<nbsp/>-plane, not on the surface. Two different level curves of the
			same function can <fillin characters="6"/> <nbsp/>cross, because a
			point cannot have <fillin characters="4"/> <nbsp/>different outputs.
		</p>
		<p component="key">
			A level curve lives in the <m>\underline{\textbf{xy}}</m>-plane, not
			on the surface. Two different level curves of the same function can
			<m>\underline{\textbf{never}}</m> cross, because a point cannot have
			<m>\underline{\textbf{two}}</m> different outputs.
		</p>

		<!-- worked problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="1in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Let <m>g(x,y) = 4x^2 + y^2</m>. Sketch the level curves for
					<m>c = 0,\ 4,\ 16</m> on the axes below, and describe the
					family in words.
				</p>
				<image width="52%">
					<shortdescription>A blank set of coordinate axes with a light grid, for sketching.</shortdescription>
					<latex-image>
	\begin{tikzpicture}
	\begin{axis}[axis lines=middle, xmin=-5, xmax=5, ymin=-5, ymax=5, grid=both, grid style={gray!25}, width=7.5cm, height=7.5cm, xtick={-4,-2,2,4}, ytick={-4,-2,2,4}, xlabel=$x$, ylabel=$y$, tick label style={font=\footnotesize}]
	\end{axis}
	\end{tikzpicture}
					</latex-image>
				</image>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Let <m>g(x,y) = 4x^2 + y^2</m>. Sketch the level curves for
					<m>c = 0,\ 4,\ 16</m>, and describe the family in words.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					Setting <m>4x^2+y^2=c</m>:
					<ul>
						<li><m>c=0</m>: only the single point
							<m>(0,0)</m> (a degenerate curve).</li>
						<li><m>c=4</m>: <m>\frac{x^2}{1}+\frac{y^2}{4}=1</m>, an
							ellipse through <m>(\pm 1,0)</m> and <m>(0,\pm 2)</m>.</li>
						<li><m>c=16</m>: <m>\frac{x^2}{4}+\frac{y^2}{16}=1</m>, a
							larger ellipse through <m>(\pm 2,0)</m> and
							<m>(0,\pm 4)</m>.</li>
					</ul>
					The level curves are concentric ellipses, twice as tall as
					they are wide, growing outward as <m>c</m> increases. The
					surface is an elliptic paraboloid opening upward; it steepens as
					we climb, so evenly-spaced heights would give ellipses that
					crowd closer together — the contour-spacing idea we return to
					below.
				</p>
				<image width="52%">
					<shortdescription>Concentric ellipses centered at the origin, twice as tall as wide (the level curves of 4x^2+y^2 for c=4 and c=16), with the origin marked for c=0.</shortdescription>
					<latex-image>
	\begin{tikzpicture}
	\begin{axis}[axis lines=middle, xmin=-5, xmax=5, ymin=-5, ymax=5, grid=both, grid style={gray!25}, width=7.5cm, height=7.5cm, xtick={-4,-2,2,4}, ytick={-4,-2,2,4}, xlabel=$x$, ylabel=$y$, tick label style={font=\footnotesize}, legend style={font=\footnotesize}]
	\addplot[domain=0:360, samples=120, thick, blue]  ({cos(x)},   {2*sin(x)});
	\addplot[domain=0:360, samples=120, thick, red]   ({2*cos(x)}, {4*sin(x)});
	\addplot[only marks, mark=*, black, mark size=1pt] coordinates {(0,0)};
	\legend{$c=4$,$c=16$,$c=0$}
	\end{axis}
	\end{tikzpicture}
					</latex-image>
				</image>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<p><alert>Your turn.</alert> Work with a neighbor.</p>

		<!-- practice problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="1in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Let <m>f(x,y) = x^2 - y^2</m>. Sketch the level curves for
					<m>c = -4,\ 0,\ 4</m> on the axes below, say what kind of curve
					each one is, and note what happens exactly at <m>c=0</m>.
				</p>
				<image width="52%">
					<shortdescription>A blank set of coordinate axes with a light grid, for sketching.</shortdescription>
					<latex-image>
	\begin{tikzpicture}
	\begin{axis}[axis lines=middle, xmin=-5, xmax=5, ymin=-5, ymax=5, grid=both, grid style={gray!25}, width=7.5cm, height=7.5cm, xtick={-4,-2,2,4}, ytick={-4,-2,2,4}, xlabel=$x$, ylabel=$y$, tick label style={font=\footnotesize}]
	\end{axis}
	\end{tikzpicture}
					</latex-image>
				</image>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Let <m>f(x,y) = x^2 - y^2</m>. Sketch the level curves for
					<m>c = -4,\ 0,\ 4</m>, say what kind of curve each one is, and
					note what happens exactly at <m>c=0</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					<m>x^2-y^2=c</m> is a hyperbola for <m>c \ne 0</m>:
					<ul>
						<li><m>c=4</m>: <m>x^2-y^2=4</m>, a hyperbola opening
							left/right through <m>(\pm 2,0)</m>.</li>
						<li><m>c=-4</m>: <m>y^2-x^2=4</m>, a hyperbola opening
							up/down through <m>(0,\pm 2)</m>.</li>
						<li><m>c=0</m>: <m>x^2=y^2</m>, i.e. the pair of lines
							<m>y=x</m> and <m>y=-x</m> — the level set degenerates to
							two lines that intersect at the origin.</li>
					</ul>
					The surface is a saddle; the crossing lines at <m>c=0</m> pass
					through the saddle point at the origin.
				</p>
				<image width="52%">
					<shortdescription>Hyperbolas opening left-right for c=4 and up-down for c=-4, with the dashed lines y=+/-x for c=0 crossing at the origin.</shortdescription>
					<latex-image>
	\begin{tikzpicture}
	\begin{axis}[axis lines=middle, xmin=-5, xmax=5, ymin=-5, ymax=5, grid=both, grid style={gray!25}, width=7.5cm, height=7.5cm, xtick={-4,-2,2,4}, ytick={-4,-2,2,4}, xlabel=$x$, ylabel=$y$, tick label style={font=\footnotesize}, legend style={font=\footnotesize}]
	\addplot[domain=-1.5:1.5, samples=60, thick, blue] ({exp(x)+exp(-x)},   {exp(x)-exp(-x)});
	\addplot[domain=-1.5:1.5, samples=60, thick, blue] ({-(exp(x)+exp(-x))},{exp(x)-exp(-x)});
	\addplot[domain=-1.5:1.5, samples=60, thick, red]  ({exp(x)-exp(-x)},   {exp(x)+exp(-x)});
	\addplot[domain=-1.5:1.5, samples=60, thick, red]  ({exp(x)-exp(-x)},   {-(exp(x)+exp(-x))});
	\addplot[domain=-5:5, samples=2, dashed, green!50!black] {x};
	\addplot[domain=-5:5, samples=2, dashed, green!50!black] {-x};
	\legend{$c=4$,,$c=-4$,,$c=0$}
	\end{axis}
	\end{tikzpicture}
					</latex-image>
				</image>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 3: Level surfaces
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><alert>III. Level surfaces.</alert></p>

		<p>
			We cannot graph a function <m>F(x,y,z)</m> of three variables — that
			would need four dimensions. The substitute for the graph is the
			<term>level surface</term> at value <m>c</m>,
			<md>
				\{(x,y,z) : F(x,y,z) = c\},
			</md>
			the three-variable analogue of a level curve: a surface in space on
			which <m>F</m> is constant.
		</p>

		<!-- reading-check pair 3 -->
		<p component="stu">
			A function of two variables is pictured by <fillin characters="6"/>
			<nbsp/>curves in a plane; a function of three variables is pictured by
			level <fillin characters="9"/> <nbsp/>in space. In both cases we drop
			the output dimension and record only where the output is
			<fillin characters="9"/>.
		</p>
		<p component="key">
			A function of two variables is pictured by
			<m>\underline{\textbf{level}}</m> curves in a plane; a function of
			three variables is pictured by level
			<m>\underline{\textbf{surfaces}}</m> in space. In both cases we drop
			the output dimension and record only where the output is
			<m>\underline{\textbf{constant}}</m>.
		</p>

		<!-- practice problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="1in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Describe the level surfaces of <m>F(x,y,z) = x^2 + y^2 + z^2</m>
					for <m>c = 0,\ 1,\ 9</m>, sketching them on the axes below. What
					goes wrong if you ask for the level surface at <m>c = -1</m>?
				</p>
				<image width="50%">
					<shortdescription>A blank set of three-dimensional coordinate axes, for sketching level surfaces.</shortdescription>
					<latex-image>
	\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
	\draw[->] (0,0,0) -- (4,0,0) node[anchor=north east] {$x$};
	\draw[->] (0,0,0) -- (0,4,0) node[anchor=north west] {$y$};
	\draw[->] (0,0,0) -- (0,0,4) node[anchor=south] {$z$};
	\end{tikzpicture}
					</latex-image>
				</image>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Describe the level surfaces of <m>F(x,y,z) = x^2 + y^2 + z^2</m>
					for <m>c = 0,\ 1,\ 9</m>. What goes wrong if you ask for the
					level surface at <m>c = -1</m>?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					<m>x^2+y^2+z^2=c</m> is a sphere of radius <m>\sqrt{c}</m>
					centered at the origin:
					<ul>
						<li><m>c=1</m>: the unit sphere;</li>
						<li><m>c=9</m>: a sphere of radius <m>3</m>;</li>
						<li><m>c=0</m>: just the origin (a degenerate sphere).</li>
					</ul>
					The level surfaces are nested spheres. For <m>c=-1</m> there are
					no points at all: a sum of three squares can never be negative,
					so that level surface is empty.
				</p>
				<image width="50%">
					<shortdescription>Two nested spheres centered at the origin, of radius 1 and radius 3, drawn as circles with dashed equator ellipses.</shortdescription>
					<latex-image>
	\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.9]
	\draw[->] (-3.5,0) -- (3.5,0) node[right] {$y$};
	\draw[->] (0,-3.5) -- (0,3.5) node[above] {$z$};
	\draw[thick, blue] (0,0) circle (1);
	\draw[thick, blue, dashed] (0,0) ellipse (1 and 0.34);
	\draw[thick, red] (0,0) circle (3);
	\draw[thick, red, dashed] (0,0) ellipse (3 and 1.02);
	\node[blue] at (1.1,1.0) {$c=1$};
	\node[red] at (2.4,2.2) {$c=9$};
	\end{tikzpicture}
					</latex-image>
				</image>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<!-- misconception check: single exercise, solution instructor-only -->
		<exercise xml:id="ws-r1-tf-levelcurve">
			<statement>
				<p>
					<alert>True or False.</alert> The level curve <m>f(x,y)=c</m> is
					a curve lying <em>on</em> the surface <m>z=f(x,y)</m> in space.
					Explain.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution component="key">
				<p>
					<term>False.</term> The level curve lives in the
					<m>xy</m>-plane (the domain). The set of points at height
					<m>c</m> <em>on</em> the surface is a curve in space; its
					<em>shadow</em> straight down onto the <m>xy</m>-plane is the
					level curve. Level curve = the projection, not the curve on the
					surface itself.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 4: Reading a contour map (application) + looking ahead
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><alert>IV. Application: reading a contour map.</alert></p>

		<p>
			Contour maps are everywhere outside class: elevation on a hiking map,
			pressure on a weather chart, or output in economics. A
			<term>Cobb&#8211;Douglas</term> production model
			<m>P(L,K) = L^{1/2}K^{1/2}</m> gives output <m>P</m> from labor
			<m>L</m> and capital <m>K</m>; its level curves <m>P=c</m> are called
			<term>isoquants</term> — input combinations that produce the same
			output.
		</p>

		<!-- worked application (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="1in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					For <m>P(L,K)=L^{1/2}K^{1/2}</m> (with <m>L,K &gt; 0</m>), write
					the isoquant <m>P=6</m> as a formula <m>K=\,?</m> in terms of
					<m>L</m>, and sketch it on the axes below. Reading the map: if
					labor <m>L</m> is cheap and capital <m>K</m> is expensive, does
					the isoquant say to use more <m>L</m> or more <m>K</m> to hit
					<m>P=6</m>?
				</p>
				<image width="52%">
					<shortdescription>A blank set of coordinate axes with a light grid, for sketching.</shortdescription>
					<latex-image>
	\begin{tikzpicture}
	\begin{axis}[axis lines=middle, xmin=-5, xmax=5, ymin=-5, ymax=5, grid=both, grid style={gray!25}, width=7.5cm, height=7.5cm, xtick={-4,-2,2,4}, ytick={-4,-2,2,4}, xlabel=$x$, ylabel=$y$, tick label style={font=\footnotesize}]
	\end{axis}
	\end{tikzpicture}
					</latex-image>
				</image>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					For <m>P(L,K)=L^{1/2}K^{1/2}</m> (with <m>L,K &gt; 0</m>), write
					the isoquant <m>P=6</m> as a formula <m>K=\,?</m> in terms of
					<m>L</m>, and sketch it. Reading the map: if labor <m>L</m> is
					cheap and capital <m>K</m> is expensive, does the isoquant say
					to use more <m>L</m> or more <m>K</m> to hit <m>P=6</m>?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					<m>L^{1/2}K^{1/2}=6 \Rightarrow LK = 36 \Rightarrow
					K = \dfrac{36}{L}</m>. The isoquant is a hyperbola-shaped
					curve falling as <m>L</m> grows (for <m>L,K&gt;0</m>). Because
					you can slide along the isoquant to trade capital for labor at
					fixed output, cheap labor / expensive capital pushes you toward
					the low-<m>K</m>, high-<m>L</m> end of the curve: use more
					<m>L</m>.
				</p>
				<image width="52%">
					<shortdescription>Three falling isoquant curves K=c^2/L in the first quadrant, for output levels P=2, 4, and 6.</shortdescription>
					<latex-image>
	\begin{tikzpicture}
	\begin{axis}[axis lines=left, xmin=0, xmax=12, ymin=0, ymax=12, grid=both, grid style={gray!25}, width=7.5cm, height=7cm, xlabel={$L$ (labor)}, ylabel={$K$ (capital)}, tick label style={font=\footnotesize}, legend style={font=\footnotesize}]
	\addplot[domain=0.34:12, samples=100, thick, blue]        {4/x};
	\addplot[domain=1.34:12, samples=100, thick, green!50!black] {16/x};
	\addplot[domain=3:12,    samples=100, thick, red]         {36/x};
	\legend{$P=2$,$P=4$,$P=6$}
	\end{axis}
	\end{tikzpicture}
					</latex-image>
				</image>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<p>
			<alert>Reading fastest change.</alert> Where contour lines are packed
			<em>close together</em>, the function is climbing steeply (small step
			in the plane, big change in output); where they are far apart it is
			nearly flat. We will make this precise soon with the
			<term>gradient</term>, which points in the direction of fastest
			increase — always perpendicular to the level curve.
		</p>
	</page>

	<conclusion>
		<p>
			<alert>Looking ahead.</alert> Level curves and level surfaces let us
			"see" a function without a fourth dimension, and the spacing of the
			contours already hints at how fast the function changes. Our next
			review makes that rate of change precise: <term>partial
			derivatives</term> measure how <m>f</m> changes as we move parallel to
			each axis, and assembling them into the <term>gradient</term> recovers
			exactly the "steepest, perpendicular to the contours" direction we
			just eyeballed.
		</p>
	</conclusion>

</worksheet>
